Author: ca333#0118
Content:
@Steve Lee @linuxcaptain - yes, CC could be used in 'endless' different IoT tech usecases. Just imagine a special IoT smart door for places you have to pay entry - the door has an interface to open/close the door. The IoT device software connects to a kmd rpc cc interface and utilize CC tech to handle access/auth/payment plus it can create an unforgeable accesslog thanks to the dPoW technology - this was one from thousands CC IoT usecases. 

Slotmachine (HW) with CC is a cool one - if you give James some raspberry pi slotmachine opensource game written in C i am sure he could transform it into a 'CCfied' version in no time and your rasbPI slotmachine turns a CC Slotmachine - with SLOT tokens for example.

Author: ca333#0118
Content: with rasbPI you need either gateway solution/rpc interface access in same net (from PI) or SPV CC. If you wanted it native i think there are limitations with ARM arch. Without PI and just on computer it likely is much simpler to code.

Author: ca333#0118
Content: yes @linuxcaptain - Komodo can natively use blockchain as database-system with simplified r/w interface. And your point was actually a good example - the data you name such as sensor data is optimal for BC storage since very tiny.
